Transfer Learning on Google Colab¶

Classifying Flower Images¶

Author: Tahmidul Islam¶

Date: 11/27/2020

When there is not a tons of training data is available moreover number of class is large, it is difficult to train a large deep learning model. Large deep learning models has hundred of thousands of parameters which requires lots of data to fine tune. Transfer learning is an excellent way to handle this type of problem. In transfer learning, we generally use a pre-trained model on a very large set and utilize the model architecture and estimated parameters. We discuss three modifications:

  • Initialize with pretrained Resnet 34 and estimate all the parameters using flower training data
  • Initialize with pretrained Resnet 34 and estimate all the parameters using augmented flower training data using the cutout method
  • Initialize with pretrained Resnet 34 and estimate only the final layer using flower training data with cutout modification

Data¶

First we explore the provided Flower dataset. This dataset is provided by Maria-Elena Nilsback and Andrew Zisserman (http://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~vgg/data/flowers/102/). It contains color images of 102 different types of flowers. Our task is to predict the category of the flower given an image of a flower.

We see the training and validation set as 10 images per class where the test data has imbalance. All the training, testing and validation images are in one folder 'jpg'. We need to create root folders 'train', 'test' and 'valid' and create subfolders corresponding to their label.

# Run this just once to create folder structure
from shutil import copyfile

filename = os.listdir(dirname + '/jpg')
for i in filename:
  name = 'jpg/' + i

Transfer learning: Resnet 34¶

We use the pre-trained model Resnet 34 to perform image classification. Here, we intialize with Resnet 34 which was trained on Imagenet 1000. After initialization we have a fully connected final layer corresponding to our flower dataset.

Data processing¶

We use the Imageloader of Pytorch to load the data. Random resize, crop and normalization have been applied to preprocess the data.

def imshow(inp, title=None):
    """Imshow for Tensor."""
    inp = inp.numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
    mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
    std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    inp = std * inp + mean
    inp = np.clip(inp, 0, 1)
    plt.imshow(inp)
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)
    plt.pause(0.001)  # pause a bit so that plots are updated

Model¶

We use the pretrained Resnet 34 and retrain the model. The learning rate scheduler changes the learning rate every 7 epochs by a factor 0f 0.1. Number of epoch is set to 25 but is recommended it is increased in real application.

In [41]:
def train_model(model, criterion, optimizer, scheduler, num_epochs=25):
    since = time.time()

    best_model_wts = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())
    best_acc = 0.0

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        print('Epoch {}/{}'.format(epoch, num_epochs - 1))
        print('-' * 10)

        # Each epoch has a training and validation phase
        for phase in ['train', 'test', 'valid']:
            if phase == 'train':
                model.train()  # Set model to training mode
            else:
                model.eval()   # Set model to evaluate mode

            running_loss = 0.0
            running_corrects = 0

            # Iterate over data.
            for inputs, labels in dataloaders[phase]:
                inputs = inputs.to(device)
                labels = labels.to(device)

                # zero the parameter gradients
                optimizer.zero_grad()

                # forward
                # track history if only in train
                with torch.set_grad_enabled(phase == 'train'):
                    outputs = model(inputs)
                    _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
                    loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

                    # backward + optimize only if in training phase
                    if phase == 'train':
                        loss.backward()
                        optimizer.step()

                # statistics
                running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
                running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)
            if phase == 'train':
                scheduler.step()

            epoch_loss = running_loss / dataset_sizes[phase]
            epoch_acc = running_corrects.double() / dataset_sizes[phase]

            print('{} Loss: {:.4f} Acc: {:.4f}'.format(
                phase, epoch_loss, epoch_acc))

            # deep copy the model
            if phase == 'valid' and epoch_acc > best_acc:
                best_acc = epoch_acc
                best_model_wts = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())

        print()

    time_elapsed = time.time() - since
    print('Training complete in {:.0f}m {:.0f}s'.format(
        time_elapsed // 60, time_elapsed % 60))
    print('Best val Acc: {:4f}'.format(best_acc))

    # load best model weights
    model.load_state_dict(best_model_wts)
    return model
In [42]:
def visualize_model(model, num_images=6):
    was_training = model.training
    model.eval()
    images_so_far = 0
    fig = plt.figure()

    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(dataloaders['test']):
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)

            for j in range(inputs.size()[0]):
                images_so_far += 1
                ax = plt.subplot(num_images//2, 2, images_so_far)
                ax.axis('off')
                ax.set_title('predicted: {}'.format(class_names[preds[j]]))
                imshow(inputs.cpu().data[j])

                if images_so_far == num_images:
                    model.train(mode=was_training)
                    return
        model.train(mode=was_training)

model_ft = models.resnet34(pretrained=True)

model_ft.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(class_names))

model_ft = model_ft.to(device)

criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

# Observe that all parameters are being optimized
optimizer_ft = optim.SGD(model_ft.parameters(), lr=0.001, momentum=0.9)

# Decay LR by a factor of 0.1 every 7 epochs
exp_lr_scheduler = lr_scheduler.StepLR(optimizer_ft, step_size=5, gamma=0.1)

Cropout for regularization¶
Furthermore, we apply the cropout regularization technique which augments the dataset by randomly removing patches from the image. We choose the number of patch to be 01 and the size of the patch to be 50 pixels.











In [46]:



     


# cutout function
import torch
import numpy as np


class Cutout(object):
    """Randomly mask out one or more patches from an image.
    Args:
        n_holes (int): Number of patches to cut out of each image.
        length (int): The length (in pixels) of each square patch.
    """
    def __init__(self, n_holes, length):
        self.n_holes = n_holes
        self.length = length

    def __call__(self, img):
        """
        Args:
            img (Tensor): Tensor image of size (C, H, W).
        Returns:
            Tensor: Image with n_holes of dimension length x length cut out of it.
        """
        h = img.size(1)
        w = img.size(2)

        mask = np.ones((h, w), np.float32)

        for n in range(self.n_holes):
            y = np.random.randint(h)
            x = np.random.randint(w)

            y1 = np.clip(y - self.length // 2, 0, h)
            y2 = np.clip(y + self.length // 2, 0, h)
            x1 = np.clip(x - self.length // 2, 0, w)
            x2 = np.clip(x + self.length // 2, 0, w)

            mask[y1: y2, x1: x2] = 0.

        mask = torch.from_numpy(mask)
        mask = mask.expand_as(img)
        img = img * mask

        return img

Freezing Resnet parameters¶
Now we freeze all the weights of the retrained network and only compute weights of the final layer with cropout data augmentation.

model_conv = torchvision.models.resnet34(pretrained=True)

    param.requires_grad = False

# Parameters of newly constructed modules have requires_grad=True by default

model_conv.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(class_names))

model_conv = model_conv.to(device)

criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

# Decay LR by a factor of 0.1 every 7 epochs

Conclusion¶
We applied transfer learning technique to classify flower images. With the help of the pretrained network Resnet 34, we achieved satisfactory accuracy using only 25 epochs. Accuracy-wise we got the best performance by retraining the Resnet with random cropout data augmentation. The fastest execution time was found for freezing Resnet except for the final layer. We recommend retraining the Resnet and utilize data augmentation and regularization techniques like cropout.
